Mystery solved: Why we can't tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from tickling themselves. Scientists at the Humboldt University in Berlin found this out by using experiments on rats, as they reported on Thursday evening. They also reported that progress had been made in understanding why children resist tickling so violently only to demand more.
Finally, it was discovered that the mere approach of a tickling hand triggers laughter before it even touches it, because of a deep layer in the cerebrum that triggers laughter when the tickling is expected.
According to the report, previous research has shown that rats respond to human tickling with ultrasonic "laughter" transmitted by the part of the cerebral cortex that is central to processing haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed during self-touching
It had been assumed that the brain could distinguish between self-touch and other people's touch - that is why people cannot tickle themselves. But the Berlin researchers found in experiments on rats that laughter is suppressed, as is the activity of the relevant area of the cerebral cortex, when a person touches himself. This is also true when living things clean themselves. During the contact and tickling by others, however, the activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh have been increased.
But if the self-touch and the other person's touch occur at the same time, the laughter is also suppressed, which suggests that the rat brain just can't distinguish between self-touch and other people's touch, and the new findings suggest that people can't tickle themselves because self-touch activates a brake in the cerebellum.
The rats were also trained to tickle themselves, and in the experiment they sometimes stopped this initiation prematurely, displayed flight or fear stiffness, and this ambivalence was similar to that of children.
