Warning: Smartphone is NOT to be charged wirelessly
Practical but Harmful
Inductive technology via Qi standard is extremely practical, but should not be used.
Since several new smartphones have recently been launched that support wireless charging and are selling very well - above all the new iPhone 11 models - we would like to recall a study from early July. Wireless charging of mobile devices is extremely practical, but not necessarily recommended.
Higher temperatures increase battery life
Researchers warn against wireless charging of smartphones. According to the University of Warwick, this is extremely harmful to the devices. The reason for this is the significantly greater heat generation. If you charge a mobile phone normally by cable, the battery heats up to 27 degrees within three hours. When wireless charging, however, the researchers have always measured over 30 degrees even with perfect orientation of the smartphone on the charging pad. If the mobile phone is located a little near the coil, the temperature rises even higher. In addition, the wattage of the charging pad also rises, which in turn drives up the power consumption.
Capacity and lifetime
According to the researchers, the temperature is a crucial factor in battery durability. Every single degree plays a role. When charged at higher temperatures, the battery not only loses capacity, but it also doesn't last as long overall. The lifespan is therefore shorter. The researchers therefore advise to always charge the smartphone by cable. Since a battery replacement in modern smartphones is always associated with high costs, this should be a helpful tip. Apple has recently even increased the cost of an battery charger once again - and for all iPhones.
Practical
The technology is extremely convenient: simply put the device on a charging pad - which is now installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels and cars - and the battery is charged without the hassle of cable salad and plugging in the plug.
