If the provider promises too much
If the Internet connection always seems to be much slower than advertised by the provider, there are various test options.
The Internet contract does not require blind trust in the speed data provided by the providers, but customers can check for themselves how much of the speed is actually achieved if there are any anomalies.
The Commission notes that the Commission has not yet decided whether the measure is compatible with the internal market.
If the connection always seems to be much slower than advertised by the provider, there are various test options: the measuring tools of the Federal Network Agency (BNetzA) measure the actual data transmission rates and compare them with the rate agreed in the contract.
'However, the tests of the suppliers are carried out according to supplier-specific specifications and are therefore not uniformly and objectively calculated', the Bavarian Consumer Centre notes on its website.
If the connection is significantly slower than advertised, customers may set the provider a reasonable period of time, usually 14 days, to deliver the promised service, preferably in writing by letter of objection.
If repeated requests fail, customers can quit and possibly claim damages, but if they fail, only a lawsuit will help.
