Doping: Further Russian manipulation found
Material from the Moscow analysis lab is being manipulated, says David Howman, former director of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) and now head of integrity at the World Athletics Federation.
With the start of the World Championships in Athletics, new details about the doping scandal in Russia are coming to light - and they destroy the little credibility that Russian sport had regained at the beginning of the year and even in a small way.
In December 2014, systematic fraud in Russian sports was revealed. The WADA had banned the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (Rusada) for three years. During this time, Russian athletes were not completely banned from the world stage. The International Olympic Committee, after individual examination, allowed around 270 athletes of the country to compete at the 2016 Summer Games in Rio under a neutral flag, at the Winter Games in February 2018, 168 Russian athletes were at the start.
No positive results were found
The following September, WADA lifted the Rusada ban again, but requested access to the laboratory and the samples in question. The data was to reveal the extent of the cover-up of doping cases in the state doping. They were to help to punish athletes afterwards. Three months later they were finally delivered.
The head of the IAAF's Independent Integrity Commission (AIU) has now confirmed that the data from the Moscow analysis lab on doping was manipulated. "Yes. We received the data nine months ago. We should check whether the task force received the correct data", David Howman said in an interview with the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung on Friday. "We found numerous discrepancies between the data that WADA received from a whistleblower and the data it received from the Russians in January".
The World Cup not affected
This confirms the position of the IAAF: the Athletics Federation is the only organization that maintains the ban on Russia. At the World Championships in Doha, 30 Russian athletes start under a neutral flag. They had to prove that they train outside the Russian system and undergo tests.
Earlier this week, WADA had already put the manipulation in the open and asked Russia to respond to the allegations within three weeks, threatening to re-block Rusada and, in the worst case, ban it from the 2020 Tokyo Olympics.
